<section class="section" aria-labelledby="etiquette-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h1 id="etiquette-title">Brazil cultural etiquette for travelers</h1>
    <p class="section-note">
      Understanding Brazilian etiquette helps you connect with locals, travel more respectfully, and make better memories. Brazil is warm, expressive, and social, and a few local habits can make your visit more comfortable and enjoyable.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="etiquette-greeting-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="etiquette-greeting-title">Greetings and first impressions</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      A friendly greeting sets the tone for most interactions in Brazil. Simple words and a smile can make local people feel comfortable with you.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>Use "Olá" or "Bom dia" when you meet someone, and say "Boa tarde" or "Boa noite" later in the day.</li>
      <li>In casual settings, people often greet with one or two cheek kisses, especially among friends.</li>
      <li>A handshake is common in business or more formal situations.</li>
      <li>Smile, make eye contact, and avoid appearing rushed when speaking with someone.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="etiquette-body-language-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="etiquette-body-language-title">Body language and personal space</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Brazilians often stand closer during conversations than travelers from other countries. This is usually a sign of warmth rather than intrusion.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>Do not be surprised by closer conversational distance in social situations.</li>
      <li>Gentle touches on the arm or shoulder can communicate friendliness.</li>
      <li>Avoid crossing your arms, which can feel defensive.</li>
      <li>Respect someone's personal items and do not touch belongings without permission.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="etiquette-speaking-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="etiquette-speaking-title">Conversation and politeness</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Polite language and patience go a long way. Brazilians value warm, engaging conversation over short, clipped answers.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>Use polite phrases like "por favor" and "obrigado / obrigada" in everyday interactions.</li>
      <li>Ask questions gently, and avoid being too direct when making requests.</li>
      <li>Compliment something you like, such as local food or a helpful service.</li>
      <li>Listen patiently and let the other person finish before you speak.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="etiquette-dining-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="etiquette-dining-title">Dining etiquette in Brazil</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Dining in Brazil is social and relaxed. Most meals are shared, and showing appreciation for food and hospitality is important.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>Wait for the host to begin eating, especially in a family or dinner setting.</li>
      <li>Try local dishes and thank the host or server if you enjoy the meal.</li>
      <li>In a churrascaria, move slowly through the buffet, and accept meat only when you are ready.</li>
      <li>Use utensils for most dishes, and avoid resting elbows on the table.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="etiquette-tipping-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="etiquette-tipping-title">Tipping and service expectations</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Tipping is common in Brazil, but it is usually already included in the bill for restaurants.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>Most restaurants add 10% service automatically, so check your bill before leaving more.</li>
      <li>If the service is excellent, it is fine to leave a small extra tip.</li>
      <li>Tip hotel porters, cleaners, and tour guides for helpful service.</li>
      <li>For taxis and ride apps, rounding up the fare is often enough.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="etiquette-public-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="etiquette-public-title">Public behavior and shared spaces</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Respect and courtesy in public spaces make a big difference, especially in busy cities and tourist areas.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>Keep your voice at a moderate volume in public transport, museums, and restaurants.</li>
      <li>Respect queues and allow people to pass in crowded sidewalks.</li>
      <li>Ask permission before taking photos of people, their homes, or private property.</li>
      <li>Dispose of trash responsibly and avoid littering on beaches or streets.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="etiquette-invitations-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="etiquette-invitations-title">Handling invitations and local events</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Brazilians often enjoy inviting people to join meals, events, and group activities. Knowing how to respond respectfully helps you avoid awkward moments.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>If someone invites you to a small local gathering, a polite thank you and an honest answer are appreciated.</li>
      <li>It is okay to say no politely if you are tired or have other plans.</li>
      <li>When you accept, arrive on time and be prepared to stay for the full event.</li>
      <li>Bring a small gift, like dessert or flowers, if you are invited to someone's home.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="etiquette-trust-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="etiquette-trust-title">How to build local trust</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Respectful actions and clear communication help you build trust with locals quickly.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>Be patient and polite when asking for directions or service.</li>
      <li>Thank people for their help, even for small favors.</li>
      <li>Accept invitations politely, but only say yes if you feel comfortable.
      </li>
      <li>Show appreciation for local customs and ask questions if you are unsure.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="etiquette-summary-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="etiquette-summary-title">Why etiquette matters on your trip</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Following local etiquette makes travel smoother, safer, and more rewarding. Small respectful actions can open more positive experiences in Brazil and help you feel welcome.
    </p>
    <p class="section-note">
      Being aware of simple customs also helps you avoid misunderstandings in busy tourist areas, restaurants, and public transport.
    </p>
